<title>
Hic-5 promotes invadopodia formation and invasion during TGF-β-induced epithelial-mesenchymal transition.
</title>

<text>

<abstract>
Transforming growth factor β (TGF-β)-stimulated epithelial-mesenchymal transition (EMT) is an important developmental process that has also been implicated in increased cell invasion and metastatic potential of cancer cells. Expression of the focal adhesion protein Hic-5 has been shown to be up-regulated in epithelial cells in response to TGF-β. Herein, we demonstrate that TGF-β-induced Hic-5 up-regulation or ectopic expression of Hic-5 in normal MCF10A cells promoted increased extracellular matrix degradation and invasion through the formation of invadopodia. Hic-5 was tyrosine phosphorylated in an Src-dependent manner after TGF-β stimulation, and inhibition of Src activity or overexpression of a Y38/60F nonphosphorylatable mutant of Hic-5 inhibited matrix degradation and invasion. RhoC, but not RhoA, was also required for TGF-β- and Hic-5-induced matrix degradation. Hic-5 also induced matrix degradation, cell migration, and invasion in the absence of TGF-β via Rac1 regulation of p38 MAPK. These data identify Hic-5 as a critical mediator of TGF-β-stimulated invadopodia formation, cell migration, and invasion.
</abstract>

<sections.0>
Introduction
pithelial tissues have extensive cellβ€“cell junction networks that promote apical and basolateral cell polarity as well as intercellular communication, and restrict cell motility (hristiansen and ajasekaran, 2006). pithelialβ€“mesenchymal transition () results in the coordinated dissolution of cellβ€“cell adhesions, loss of apical-basolateral polarity, and the reorganization of the actin cytoskeleton to promote mesenchymal cell migration and invasion (endt and chiemann, 2009).  is essential for normal development, but has also been linked to the early stages of cancer progression (u et al., 2009).
-² is a cytokine known to have a biphasic effect on tumor progression. lthough -² can function as a tumor suppressor through inhibition of cell proliferation of nontransformed cells, it has also been shown to function as an oncogene by inducing  to promote increased invasion in cancer cells as well as in normal breast epithelial cells (umont and rteaga, 2000; im et al., 2004; andal et al., 2008); it does this via stimulation of both -dependent and -independent pathways (ian et al., 2011). e previously reported that induction of  in -²β€“stimulated mammary gland and kidney epithelial cells results in increased expression of the focal adhesion protein ic-5 (hydrogen peroxide inducible clone 5, also known as -²1i1 and 55; hibanuma et al., 1994; ujimoto et al., 1999) to promote increased cell migration (umbarello et al., 2005; umbarello and urner, 2007).
ic-5 was first identified as a hydrogen peroxide and -²β€“inducible gene (hibanuma et al., 1994), and is a member of the paxillin superfamily of focal adhesion adaptor proteins (homas et al., 1999; rown and urner, 2004). oth ic-5 and paxillin function as molecular scaffolds, sharing many of the same binding partners and coordinating ho ase activity to regulate focal adhesion dynamics and actin cytoskeleton remodeling during cell migration (rown and urner, 2004; etey et al., 2005; umbarello and urner, 2007; eakin and urner, 2008). espite these similarities, the relationship between ic-5 and paxillin is complex, with each controlling distinct aspects of adhesion signaling and cell migration in 2 and 3 matrices (hibanuma et al., 1994, 1997; ujita et al., 1998; atsuya et al., 1998; eakin and urner, 2011).
ancer cells frequently form specialized adhesion structures in vitro, termed invadopodia, that have the ability to degrade underlying extracellular matrix to promote invasion (estaing et al., 2011). he ho ases play key roles in the assembly and maturation of invadopodia. ac1 and dc42 have been implicated in the actin nucleation necessary for their formation (inder et al., 1999; ead et al., 2003), whereas ho. A and RhoC are required for invadopodia maturation (Bravo-Cordero et al., 2011; Destaing et al., 2011). Importantly, RhoC is also up-regulated during EMT (Hutchison et al., 2009), and elevated RhoC activity, rather than RhoA, has been closely linked to increased tumor malignancy in vivo (Clark et al., 2000). Although paxillin has been implicated in invadopodia dynamics (Badowski et al., 2008), a role for Hic-5 has not been investigated.
In this study, we identify Hic-5 as a key mediator of TGF-Ξ²β€“induced invasion and formation of matrix degrading invadopodia in normal MCF10A breast epithelial cells. We identify Hic-5 as a novel component of invadopodia and show that Hic-5 acts upstream of RhoCβ€“ROCK and Rac1β€“p38 MAPK pathways in regulating matrix degradation and invasion. Additionally, Src kinase, another key component of invadopodia formation in transformed cells (Linder, 2007), mediates Hic-5 tyrosine phosphorylation in response to TGF-Ξ², which in turn promotes Src-dependent development of the invasive phenotype in normal MCF10A cells.
