<sections.1>
Results
-² stimulation results in a ic-5β€“dependent increase in matrix degradation, motility, and invasion. We have previously shown that Hic-5 is up-regulated upon TGF-Ξ²β€“stimulated EMT (Tumbarello and Turner, 2007). Accordingly, Western blotting of TGF-Ξ²β€“stimulated normal human breast epithelial MCF10A cells stably expressing GFP confirmed the induction of Hic-5, as well as Ξ± smooth muscle actin (Fig. 1 A), another established marker of EMT (Sebe et al., 2008). A corresponding loss of the epithelial cellβ€“cell junctions and cortical actin distribution, increase in stress fibers, and robust Hic-5 localization to focal adhesions, which are indicative of EMT, were also observed (Fig. S1; Tumbarello et al., 2005; Tumbarello and Turner, 2007).Figure 1.TGF-Ξ² treatment of MCF10A cells results in Hic-5β€“dependent increased matrix degradation, motility, and invasion. (A) Western blot analysis of MCF10A cells treated with vehicle and TGF-Ξ². TGF-Ξ²β€“treated cells have increased Hic-5 and Ξ± smooth muscle actin protein expression. Up-regulated Hic-5 is efficiently depleted using two independent human-specific Hic-5 siRNAs (hHic-5). Paxillin is efficiently depleted using two independent siRNAs. Molecular mass standards are indicated next to the gel blots in kilodaltons. (B) Vehicle and TGF-Ξ²β€“treated MCF10A cells plated on fluorescent 488β€“gelatin. TGF-Ξ²β€“treated cells demonstrate increased degradation of underlying matrix, which is reduced with Hic-5 RNAi but not paxillin RNAi. Bars: (main panels) 20 Βµm; (insets) 4 Βµm. (C) Quantitation of cells associated with matrix degradation. (D) Quantitation of the area of matrix degraded per cell area. **, P < 0.005; ***, P < 0.0005. Breaks in the x axis indicate separate sets of experiments, each n = 3. Error bars represent the standard error of the mean.Increased cell migration and invasion are hallmarks of EMT and also key indicators of metastatic potential (Yilmaz and Christofori, 2009). Because TGF-Ξ² stimulation of epithelial cells has previously been shown to also promote cell invasion (Destaing et al., 2011), vehicle and TGF-Ξ²β€“treated MCF10A cells were plated on fluorescent gelatin to determine their ability to degrade ECM (Fig. 1 B). A highly significant increase in matrix degradation was observed in TGF-Ξ²β€“treated MCF10A cells (Fig. 1, C and D). To determine whether Hic-5 expression played a role in TGF-Ξ²β€“induced matrix degradation, the TGF-Ξ²β€“stimulated induction of Hic-5 expression was blocked by introduction of two independent human-specific Hic-5 siRNAs (Fig. 1 A), and cells were plated on fluorescent gelatin (Fig. 1 B). The Hic-5 RNAi-treated cells displayed a significant reduction in both the area and number of cells exhibiting matrix degradation as compared with the control RNAi-treated cells (Fig. 1, C and D), demonstrating that Hic-5 is at least partially responsible for the TGF-Ξ²β€“induced matrix degradation.Paxillin, a closely related Hic-5 family member (Brown and Turner, 2004), has previously been found to be a component of invadopodia in other systems, and its tyrosine phosphorylation has been shown to play a role in invadopodia dynamics (Badowski et al., 2008). In contrast to Hic-5, paxillin is constitutively expressed in the noninvasive MCF10A cells before EMT-inducing stimuli (Tumbarello et al., 2005). Nevertheless, because paxillin becomes tyrosine phosphorylated in response to TGF-Ξ² (Tumbarello et al., 2005), we sought to determine if depletion of paxillin in TGF-Ξ²β€“stimulated cells would have an effect on matrix degradation. Paxillin was effectively knocked down using two different human paxillin-specific siRNAs (Fig. 1 A), but interestingly, knockdown cells retained their full capacity to degrade matrix (Fig. 1, Bβ€“D), which suggests that paxillin signaling is not essential for matrix degradation in this system.Hic-5 localizes to invadopodia in TGF-Ξ²β€“treated MCF10A cellsThe regions of matrix degradation observed in TGF-Ξ²β€“treated MCF10A cells frequently coincided with phalloidin staining of F-actinβ€“rich puncta (Fig. 1 B), which is indicative of the formation of invasive adhesion structures called invadopodia (Linder, 2009). Invadopodia are characterized by an F-actin core enriched in actin-nucleating and binding proteins such as WASP, Arp2/3, and cortactin, and surrounded by a ring of adhesion-associated proteins including integrins, vinculin, talin, and paxillin (Destaing et al., 2011). Increased matrix degradation at these sites results from the accumulation and localized activity of both membrane-bound and secreted matrix metalloproteinases (MMPs; Gimona and Buccione, 2006). Although TGF-Ξ² has been reported to increase invasion in MCF10A cells via MMP activity (Kim et al., 2004), it had not previously been determined whether the cells form invadopodia. Additional staining of the TGF-Ξ²β€“treated MCF10A cells revealed that endogenous Hic-5 and paxillin colocalized in a ring surrounding the punctate areas of degraded matrix (Fig. 2 A). Actin and cortactin were colocalized in the invadopodia core overlying the areas of matrix degradation. Actopaxin (Ξ±-parvin), an actin-binding and paxillin- and Hic-5β€“associated focal adhesion protein (Nikolopoulos and Turner, 2000; WickstrΓ¶m et al., 2010), also localized to the ring structure surrounding the actin and cortactin core. These data confirm these structures as invadopodia and identify Hic-5 and actopaxin as new invadopodia constituents (Fig. 2 A).Figure 2.Hic-5 localizes to invadopodia in TGF-Ξ²β€“treated MCF10A cells. (A) TGF-Ξ²β€“treated MCF10A cells plated on fluorescent gelatin. Endogenous Hic-5 and paxillin colocalize in a ring around areas of matrix degradation, and actin and cortactin localize to the core structure. TGF-Ξ²β€“treated MCF10A cells plated on collagen show the focal adhesion protein actopaxin localized in a ring around an actin- and cortactin-containing core. Representative line profile plots demonstrate the distribution of Hic-5, paxillin, and actopaxin to the ring and actin, and cortactin to the core of invadopodia. Bars: (main panels) 10 Βµm; (insets) 1 Βµm. (B) TGF-Ξ²β€“treated cells demonstrate increased migration toward serum in a modified Boyden chamber assay. Hic-5 knockdown results in decreased migration. (C) TGF-Ξ²β€“treated cells have enhanced ability to invade through Matrigel, which is reduced with Hic-5 knockdown. *, P < 0.05; **, P < 0.005; ***, P < 0.0005. Breaks in the x axis indicate separate sets of experiments, each n = 3. Error bars represent the standard error of the mean.Invadopodia are frequently observed in cells that also demonstrate increased matrix invasion. TGF-Ξ²β€“treatment of MCF10A cells significantly enhanced cell migration and invasion through Matrigel (Fig. 2, B and C). This effect was blocked by RNAi depletion of endogenous human Hic-5 (hHic-5; Fig. 2, B and C), which indicates a requirement for Hic-5 in TGF-Ξ²β€“dependent migration and invasion.Ectopic Hic-5 expression produces phenotypic and functional characteristics of TGF-Ξ² stimulationWe have previously shown that ectopic expression of Hic-5 in MCF10A cells induces morphological changes indicative of EMT, including decreased cellβ€“cell junctions and increased actin stress fiber formation (Tumbarello and Turner, 2007). To evaluate whether there is a causal relationship between Hic-5 up-regulation and EMT-associated increases in migration, invasion, and matrix degradation, stable populations of MCF10A cells expressing either GFP or mouse GFPβ€“Hic-5 were generated. Western blot analysis confirmed expression of GFP and GFPβ€“Hic-5 (Fig. 3 A), and revealed that the level of the EMT marker Ξ±-smooth muscle actin was increased in the cells expressing GFPβ€“Hic-5. After plating on collagen, immunostaining for E-cadherin and actin demonstrated that GFP cells maintained the typical cobblestone-like morphology of epithelial cells, whereas the GFPβ€“Hic-5 cells exhibited disorganized cellβ€“cell interactions (Fig. S2 B; Schmalhofer et al., 2009). Time-lapse movies also demonstrated significant phenotypic differences between the GFP- and GFPβ€“Hic-5β€“expressing cells (Videos 1 and 2). Although the GFP cells are quite dynamic, they form and maintain stable cellβ€“cell adhesions and preferentially migrate as groups of cells, which is typical of epithelial cell migration. In contrast, the GFPβ€“Hic-5 cells make only transient cellβ€“cell contact, migrating mostly as single cells, which is typical of the mesenchymal phenotype.Figure 3.Mouse GFPβ€“Hic-5 expression in human MCF10A cells results in increased matrix degradation, motility, and invasion. (A) Western blot analysis shows expression levels of GFP, and mouse GFPβ€“Hic-5β€“overexpressing cells have increased Ξ± smooth muscle actin. GFPβ€“Hic-5 can be efficiently depleted with two independent siRNAs specific for mHic-5. Molecular mass standards are indicated next to the gel blots in kilodaltons. (B) GFP and GFPβ€“Hic-5 cells plated on fluorescent 488 gelatin. GFPβ€“Hic-5β€“expressing cells have the ability to degrade matrix, which is reversed with mHic-5 siRNA. Bar, 20 Βµm. (C) Quantitation of the percentage of cells associated with matrix degradation. (D) Quantitation of the area of matrix degraded per cell area. (E) Modified Boyden chamber assay shows that GFPβ€“Hic-5 cells have increased motility that is reversed with mHic-5 siRNA. (F) GFPβ€“Hic-5β€“expressing cells demonstrate increased invasion through Matrigel compared with GFP-expressing cells that is reversed upon knockdown of GFPβ€“Hic-5. *, P < 0.05; **, P < 0.005; ***, P < 0.0005. Breaks in the x axis indicate separate sets of experiments, each n = 3. (G) GFPβ€“Hic-5 localizes to the ring structure of invadopodia surrounding an actin core. Actin and cortactin colocalize to the core structure of invadopodia. Representative line profile plots demonstrate the distribution of GFPβ€“Hic-5 to the ring, and actin and cortactin to the core of invadopodia. Error bars represent the standard error of the mean. Bars: (main panels) 10 Βµm; (insets) 1 Βµm.To examine whether Hic-5 expression was sufficient to promote matrix degradation in the absence of a TGF-Ξ² stimulus, the GFP and GFPβ€“Hic-5β€“expressing cells were plated on fluorescent gelatin coverslips (Fig. 3 B). A highly significant increase in the number of GFPβ€“Hic-5 cells degrading matrix and the area of matrix degraded was observed as compared with GFP cells (Fig. 3, C and D). GFPβ€“Hic-5β€“expressing cells also formed actin puncta that colocalized with areas of matrix degradation (Fig. 3 B), which is indicative of invadopodia formation. As with endogenous Hic-5, the GFPβ€“Hic-5 localized to the ring structure of these invadopodia, surrounding the actin core (Fig. 3 G). Cortactin was also seen colocalized with actin at sites of matrix degradation in GFPβ€“Hic-5β€“expressing cells (Fig. 3 G). Together, these data indicate that ectopic expression of Hic-5 can induce matrix degradation and invadopodia formation in the absence of TGF-Ξ² stimulation.To assess whether the overexpression of Hic-5 is directly responsible for increased matrix degradation, the GFPβ€“Hic-5 was depleted using two independent siRNAs specific for mouse Hic-5 (mHic-5; Fig. 3 A). Knockdown of the GFPβ€“Hic-5 significantly suppressed the percentage of cells degrading matrix and the area of matrix degraded (Fig. 3, Bβ€“D). As with the TGF-Ξ²β€“treated parental MCF10A cells, depletion of endogenous paxillin in the GFPβ€“Hic-5 cells had no effect on matrix degradation (Fig. S3). GFPβ€“Hic-5β€“expressing cells also exhibited a significant increase in both migration (Fig. 3 E) and invasion through Matrigel (Fig. 3 F) as compared with the GFP control cells, which was also reversed by siRNA knockdown of the GFPβ€“Hic-5. Together, these data indicate that Hic-5 expression is both necessary and sufficient to induce invadopodia formation, invasion, and migration in MCF10A cells.Hic-5β€“induced matrix degradation and invasion requires FAK and Src activityBoth FAK and Src activity are up-regulated during TGF-Ξ²β€“induced EMT to promote invadopodia formation, and both play critical roles in cell invasion (Cicchini et al., 2008). Active FAK localizes to invadopodia, and the overexpression of FAK has been shown to enhance matrix degradation (Alexander et al., 2008; Parekh and Weaver, 2009). The activation of Src kinase is widely known to promote and be required for invadopodia formation (Bowden et al., 2006). Elevation of FAK and Src expression and activity has also been linked to tumor progression and metastasis (Provenzano and Keely, 2009). Western blot analysis showed that the levels of FAK and Src phosphorylation are both elevated in GFPβ€“Hic-5β€“expressing cells compared with their control GFP counterparts (Fig. 4 A). Pharmacological inhibition of FAK with PF573228 or Src with PP2 significantly inhibited invadopodia formation and matrix degradation (Fig. 4, B and C). In addition to matrix degradation, FAK and Src activity were also found to be necessary for Hic-5β€“induced invasion through Matrigel (Fig. 4 D).Figure 4.FAK and Src activity are necessary for GFPβ€“Hic-5β€“induced matrix degradation and invasion. (A) Western blot analysis shows increased levels of phosphorylated FAK and Src in GFPβ€“Hic-5β€“expressing MCF10A cells compared with GFP cells. Molecular mass standards are indicated next to the gel blots in kilodaltons. (B) GFPβ€“Hic-5 cells plated in the presence of FAK (PF573228) and Src (PP2) inhibitors fail to degrade matrix. Bar, 20 Βµm. (C) Quantitation of the percentage of cells associated with matrix degradation. (D) Matrigel invasion is significantly decreased in GFPβ€“Hic-5β€“expressing cells treated with the FAK and Src inhibitors. Error bars represent the standard error of the mean. **, P < 0.005; ***, P < 0.0005.Hic-5 phosphorylation contributes to matrix degradation and invasionWe have previously shown that Hic-5 is phosphorylated on tyrosine residues 38 and 60 in an EGF-dependent manner (Hetey et al., 2005), and others have observed Hic-5 tyrosine phosphorylation in response to integrin ligation, serum, lysophosphatidic acid, and osmotic stress (Fujita et al., 1998; Matsuya et al., 1998; Thomas et al., 1999; Ishino et al., 2000; Hetey et al., 2005). Analysis of the TGF-Ξ²β€“stimulated MCF10A cells demonstrated that not only is protein expression of Hic-5 induced, but that Hic-5 is also tyrosine phosphorylated (Fig. 5 A). Addition of the Src inhibitor PP2 to TGF-Ξ²β€“stimulated cells decreased Hic-5 phosphorylation, whereas the FAK inhibitor PF573228 had no effect (Fig. 5, A and B). This demonstrates that Hic-5 is phosphorylated in a Src-dependent manner.Figure 5.Hic-5 phosphorylation is required for matrix degradation and invasion. (A) Immunoprecipitation of endogenous hHic-5 from TGF-Ξ²β€“treated MCF10A cells demonstrates that Hic-5 is tyrosine phosphorylated, and inhibition of Src with PP2 reduces Hic-5 phosphorylation, whereas the FAK inhibitor PF573228 had no effect. (B) Quantitation of the ratio of tyrosine-phosphorylated Hic-5 to total Hic-5 normalized to vehicle-treated cells. (C) Immunoprecipitation of GFP, mouse GFPβ€“Hic-5, and mouse GFPβ€“Hic-5 Y38/60F shows that Y38/60 constitute the major sites of Hic-5 phosphorylation. (D) Western blot analysis shows that levels of Src pY418 are reduced in GFPβ€“Hic-5 Y38/60Fβ€“expressing cells. (E) GFPβ€“Hic-5 and GFPβ€“Hic-5 Y38/60F cells plated on fluorescent 488 gelatin show a decrease in matrix degradation in the GFPβ€“Hic-5 Y38/60F mutantβ€“expressing cells. Bar, 20 Βµm. (F) Quantitation of the percentage of cells associated with matrix degradation. (G) Quantitation of the area of degraded matrix per cell area. (H) Matrigel invasion is reduced in cells expressing the GFPβ€“Hic-5 Y38/60F mutant. (I) Treatment of mouse GFPβ€“Hic-5β€“expressing cells with TGF-Ξ² results in the up-regulation of endogenous hHic-5, which can be depleted by hHic-5 siRNA (hHic-5). Matrix degradation is not changed with TGF-Ξ² treatment or the depletion of endogenous Hic-5. (J) Treatment of GFPβ€“Hic-5 Y38/60F cells with TGF-Ξ² results in the expression of endogenous Hic-5 and an increase in matrix degradation that is reversed with RNAi of the endogenous hHic-5. Molecular mass standards are indicated next to the gel blots in kilodaltons. (K) Quantitation of the area of degraded matrix/cell area in cells transfected with active Src Y527F demonstrates that active Src (Y527F) cannot promote matrix degradation in GFP-expressing cells, but that it does so in the GFPβ€“Hic-5 and GFPβ€“Hic-5 Y38/60F cells. Error bars represent the standard error of the mean. *, P < 0.05; **, P < 0.005; ***, P < 0.0005.To determine if there was a role for Hic-5 phosphorylation in mediating the increased invasion and matrix degradation seen in Hic-5β€“expressing cells, we generated MCF10A cells stably expressing the mouse GFPβ€“Hic-5 Y38/60F mutant at a comparable level to the GFPβ€“Hic-5β€“expressing cells (Fig. S2). Western blot analysis of GFP, GFPβ€“Hic-5, and GFPβ€“Hic-5 Y38/60F immunoprecipitates confirmed that Hic-5 is tyrosine phosphorylated in the MCF10A cells and that Y38 and Y60 are the major phosphorylation sites (Fig. 5 C). Expression of the GFPβ€“Hic-5 Y38/60F mutant resulted in less Src Y418 phosphorylation as compared with the GFPβ€“Hic-5β€“expressing cells (Fig. 5 D), which suggests the existence of a positive feedback loop between Hic-5 phosphorylation and Src activity. Furthermore, the GFPβ€“Hic-5 Y38/60F mutantβ€“expressing cells exhibited significantly reduced matrix degradation and invasion through Matrigel as compared with the GFPβ€“Hic-5β€“expressing cells (Figs. 5, Eβ€“H). Expression of GFPβ€“Hic-5 Y38/60F also reduced cell migration (unpublished data). Time-lapse movies demonstrated that the GFPβ€“Hic-5 Y38/60F mutant cells exhibited characteristics of the parental epithelial cell population (Video 3), with a propensity to maintain cellβ€“cell contact as compared with GFPβ€“Hic-5 cells. Analysis of a Ξ”LD3 mutant of Hic-5, which is unable to interact with the PKL-PIX-PAK signaling axis (Brown and Turner 2004), demonstrated that this domain is not required for Hic-5β€“induced matrix degradation, motility, and invasion in these cells (Fig. 5, Fβ€“H). All GFPβ€“Hic-5 constructs express at similar levels, without stimulating endogenous Hic-5 up-regulation (Fig. S2 A and not depicted), and all have the ability to localize to adhesions (Fig. S2, B and C).Because we were unable to perform a typical RNAi rescue experiment in MCF10A cells for technical reasons, we instead used the ability of TGF-Ξ² to induce the expression of endogenous hHic-5 in the GFPβ€“Hic-5 or GFPβ€“Hic-5 Y38/60F-expressing cells, which can be subsequently blocked using siRNA specific to hHic-5 while the cells still retain expression of the mouse GFPβ€“Hic-5 constructs (Fig. 5, I and J). Induction of endogenous Hic-5 expression did not result in any further increase in matrix degradation in the GFPβ€“Hic-5 cells (Fig. 5 I). Although there was a modest increase in cells associated with matrix degradation when endogenous Hic-5 was up-regulated in the cells expressing the GFPβ€“Hic-5 Y38/60F mutant after TGF-Ξ² treatment (Fig. 5, F and J), the expression of the Y38/60F mutant acted as a dominant negative because the cells failed to degrade to the level that was observed when normal MCF10A cells are stimulated with TGF-Ξ² (Fig. 1 C). Knockdown of the TGF-Ξ²β€“induced endogenous Hic-5 with hHic-5 siRNA had no effect on matrix degradation in the GFPβ€“Hic-5β€“expressing cells (see Fig. 8 I) but decreased degradation in GFPβ€“Hic-5 Y38/60Fβ€“expressing cells back to levels comparable to untreated cells (Fig. 5 J). Collectively, these data identify a role for Src in the phosphorylation of Hic-5, which in turn is necessary for sustained Src activity and maximal Src-mediated matrix degradation and invadopodia formation. Furthermore, Hic-5 phosphorylation is required for efficient matrix degradation, migration, and invasion in MCF10A cells in response to TGF-Ξ².To determine if constitutively active Src can induce matrix degradation in MCF10A cells in the absence of TGF-Ξ² stimulation or Hic-5 expression, MCF10A GFP, GFPβ€“Hic-5, and GFPβ€“Hic-5 Y38/60F cells were transfected with the active Y527F Src mutant (Bharti et al., 2007; Buschman et al., 2009). Expression of the active Src produced a small, but nonsignificant increase in matrix degradation in the GFP-expressing cells (Fig. 5 K). However, active Src introduced into the GFPβ€“Hic-5 Y38/60F cells caused a significant increase in matrix degradation that approached the level observed in GFPβ€“Hic-5 cells with or without active Src (Fig. 5 K). These data indicate that active Src can rescue signaling downstream of the GFPβ€“Hic-5 Y38/60F mutant and also that Hic-5 expression is necessary for active Src to induce significant matrix degradation.Rac1 and RhoC but not RhoA are required for TGF-Ξ²β€“ and Hic-5β€“dependent matrix degradationPrevious studies link localized Rac1 activity to the formation of invadopodia (Head et al., 2003; Linder, 2009), and we have previously shown that Hic-5 has the ability to regulate Rac1 activity, possibly through the phosphorylation state of Hic-5 (Hetey et al., 2005). To determine if there was a role for Rac1 in Hic-5β€“induced invadopodia formation and matrix degradation, cells were plated on fluorescent gelatin in the presence of the Rac1 inhibitor NSC23766 (Pankov et al., 2005). Rac1 inhibition blocked invadopodia formation and matrix degradation in both TGF-Ξ²β€“stimulated parental MCF10A cells and unstimulated GFPβ€“Hic-5β€“expressing cells (Fig. 6, A and B).Figure 6.Rac1 is necessary for GFPβ€“Hic-5 induced matrix degradation. (A) TGF-Ξ²β€“treated MCF10A GFP cells or unstimulated mouse GFPβ€“Hic-5β€“expressing cells plated on fluorescent gelatin in the presence of vehicle or the Rac1 inhibitor NSC23766. Rac1 inhibition blocks invadopodia formation and matrix degradation. Bar, 20 Βµm. (B) Quantitation of the percentage of cells associated with matrix degradation. ***, P < 0.0005. The break in the x axis indicates separate sets of experiments, each n = 3. Error bars represent the standard error of the mean.The Rho/ROCK pathway is activated during TGF-Ξ²β€“induced EMT (Bhowmick et al., 2001a) in response to Hic-5 up-regulation (Tumbarello and Turner, 2007), and has also been implicated in invadopodia maturation (Sakurai-Yageta et al., 2008; Albiges-Rizo et al., 2009). Addition of the ROCK inhibitor Y-27632 to either the TGF-Ξ²β€“stimulated, or the GFPβ€“Hic-5β€“expressing cells significantly inhibited matrix degradation (Fig. 7, A and B). Both RhoA and RhoC can activate ROCK (Sahai and Marshall, 2002). To determine their respective roles in matrix degradation, RhoA and RhoC were individually depleted from TGF-Ξ²β€“stimulated MCF10A GFP cells (Fig. 7 C). Interestingly, RhoC knockdown significantly reduced invadopodia formation and matrix degradation, whereas depletion of RhoA had no effect (Fig. 7, D and E). Furthermore, TGF-Ξ² treatment of MCF10A GFP cells increased RhoC activity as measured by GSTβ€“Rho binding domain (RBD) pull-down assays, and depletion of endogenous Hic-5 by RNAi from TGF-Ξ²β€“stimulated cells suppressed this increase in RhoC activity (Fig. 7 F). Importantly, RhoC but not RhoA knockdown in the GFPβ€“Hic-5 cells also abrogated matrix degradation (Fig. 7, Gβ€“I). Together, these data indicate that RhoC is required for ROCK-mediated matrix degradation in MCF10A cells and that TGF-Ξ² enhances RhoC activity in a Hic-5β€“dependent manner.Figure 7.RhoCβ€“ROCK but not RhoA are required for Hic-5β€“mediated matrix degradation. (A) TGF-Ξ²β€“stimulated MCF10A GFP cells or unstimulated mouse GFPβ€“Hic-5β€“expressing MCF10A cells treated with the ROCK inhibitor Y27632 demonstrate inhibited matrix degradation. (B) Quantitation of the percentage of cells associated with matrix degradation. (C) RhoA and RhoC were efficiently depleted from the TGF-Ξ²β€“treated MCF10A GFP cells with two independent siRNAs. (D) RhoA and RhoC knockdown of TGF-Ξ²β€“treated MCF10A GFP cells plated on fluorescent gelatin. RhoC-depleted cells have inhibited ability to degrade matrix. (E) Quantitation of the percentage of cells associated with matrix degradation. (F) The GST-RBD pull-down assay demonstrates that RhoC activity is increased in TGF-Ξ²β€“treated MCF10A GFP cells, which is suppressed by depletion of TGF-Ξ²β€“induced endogenous Hic-5 using human siRNA (hHic-5). (G) RhoA and RhoC were depleted from the mouse GFPβ€“Hic-5β€“expressing MCF10A cells. Molecular mass standards are indicated next to the gel blots in kilodaltons. (H) GFPβ€“Hic-5 expressing cells treated with RhoA and RhoC RNAi plated on fluorescent gelatin. RhoC knockdown inhibits matrix degradation. (I) Quantitation of the percentage of cells associated with matrix degradation. Bars, 20 Βµm. Error bars represent the standard error of the mean. **, P < 0.005; ***, P < 0.0005.P38 MAPK but not extracellular signal-regulated kinase (ERK) 1/2 activity is necessary for Hic-5β€“mediated matrix degradation and invasionPrevious studies have indicated a role for p38 MAPK in TGF-Ξ²β€“induced MMP activity and invasion in MCF10A cells (Kim et al., 2004, 2005). It has also been well characterized that TGF-Ξ² stimulates a canonical SMAD pathway and noncanonical MAPK pathway, resulting in the phosphorylation of SMAD3 and p38 MAPK, respectively (Wendt and Schiemann, 2009). Therefore, we sought to determine if Hic-5 plays a role in either pathway. When endogenous hHic-5 was depleted by RNAi from TGF-Ξ²β€“treated cells, the levels of phospho-p38 MAPK were reduced, whereas phospho-SMAD3 levels were unaffected (Fig. 8 A).Figure 8.Matrix degradation by TGF-Ξ²β€“treated MCF10A cells or unstimulated GFPβ€“Hic-5 MCF10A cells is dependent on p38 MAPK activity but not ERK. (A) TGF-Ξ²β€“treated MCF10A GFP cells were treated with control and hHic-5 siRNAs (hHic-5). Endogenous hHic-5 depletion reduces the level of p38 MAPK phosphorylation but not SMAD3 phosphorylation. (B) TGF-Ξ²β€“treated MCF10A GFP cells were plated on fluorescent 488β€“gelatin in the presence of vehicle, MEK/ERK inhibitor U0126, or p38 MAPK inhibitor SB203580. The p38 MAPK inhibitor blocked degradation, whereas the ERK inhibitor had no effect. Bar, 20 Βµm. (C) Quantitation of TGF-Ξ²β€“treated cells degrading matrix in the presence of inhibitors. (D) Western blot analysis showing that unstimulated GFPβ€“Hic-5 cells have elevated levels of p38 MAPK phosphorylation. (E) GFPβ€“Hic-5 cells plated on fluorescent gelatin in the presence of p38 MAPK and ERK inhibitors. P38 MAPK inhibition blocked matrix degradation. Bar, 20 Βµm. (F) Quantitation of GFPβ€“Hic-5β€“expressing cells degrading matrix in the presence of inhibitors. (G) Invasion through Matrigel is reduced in GFPβ€“Hic-5β€“expressing MCF10A cells by the p38 MAPK inhibitor, but not by ERK inhibition. ***, P < 0.0005. (H) Treatment of GFPβ€“Hic-5 cells with Rac1 inhibitor NSC23766 reduces the level of phospho-p38 MAPK. Molecular mass standards are indicated next to the gel blots in kilodaltons. Error bars represent the standard error of the mean.To determine if p38 MAPK activation plays a role in the increased matrix degradation and invasion seen in the TGF-Ξ²β€“stimulated MCF10A cells, cells were plated on fluorescent-gelatin in the presence of either the p38 MAPK inhibitor SB203580 or the MEK/ERK inhibitor U1026. P38 MAPK activity but not MEK/ERK was found to be indispensable for TGF-Ξ²β€“stimulated matrix degradation (Fig. 8, B and C). Importantly, p38 MAPK activity was also elevated in the GFPβ€“Hic-5β€“expressing cells in the absence of TGF-Ξ² (Fig. 8 D), and matrix degradation in these cells, as well as invasion through Matrigel, was also selectively blocked by treatment with the p38 MAPK inhibitor SB203580 (Fig. 8, Eβ€“G). These data are consistent with previous findings that p38 MAPK is required for invasion of TGF-Ξ²β€“treated MCF10A cells and now place Hic-5 upstream of p38 MAPK activation.It has been shown that Rac1 activity can stimulate activation of p38 MAPK (Bakin et al., 2002), and Western blot analysis of the GFPβ€“Hic-5 cells treated with Rac1 inhibitor showed a decrease in p38 MAPK phosphorylation (Fig. 8 H). Together, these data identify Rac1 activation as an intermediate step in Hic-5β€“dependent invadopodia formation and associated p38 MAPK activation.
